var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"location":"api/#API-Reference","page":"API Reference","title":"API Reference","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Input","page":"API Reference","title":"Input","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Data-readers","page":"API Reference","title":"Data readers","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Fitting","page":"API Reference","title":"Fitting","text":"Available model types (pass an instance as the first argument to fit_model; omit for the default Sovová PDE model):","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Output","page":"API Reference","title":"Output","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Graphical-Interface","page":"API Reference","title":"Graphical Interface","text":"See the GUI page.","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Utilities","page":"API Reference","title":"Utilities","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#SFEModelling.ExtractionCurve","page":"API Reference","title":"SFEModelling.ExtractionCurve","text":"ExtractionCurve(; data, ...)\n\nExperimental extraction curve data and operating conditions for one experiment.\n\nRequired keyword arguments\n\ndata::Matrix{Float64}: table with column 1 = extraction times (min) and columns 2:N = cumulative extracted mass for each replicate (g). A Matrix can be read from files with TextTable or ExcelTable.\nporosity::Float64: bed porosity (dimensionless)\nx0::Float64: total extractable yield (mass fraction, kg/kg)\nsolid_density::Float64: solid density (g/cm³)\nsolvent_density::Float64: solvent density (g/cm³)\nflow_rate::Float64: solvent flow rate (cm³/min)\nbed_height::Float64: bed height (cm)\nbed_diameter::Float64: bed diameter (cm)\nparticle_diameter::Float64: particle diameter (cm)\nsolid_mass::Float64: mass of solid (g)\nsolubility::Float64: solubility (kg/kg)\n\nOptional keyword arguments\n\nnh::Int: spatial discretization steps (default: 5)\nnt::Int: temporal discretization steps (default: 2500)\n\nExample\n\ndata = TextTable(\"experiment.txt\")  # or ExcelTable(\"experiment.xlsx\")\ncurve = ExtractionCurve(data=data, porosity=0.4, ...)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"api/#SFEModelling.TextTable","page":"API Reference","title":"SFEModelling.TextTable","text":"TextTable(filename; kwargs...)\n\nRead a delimited text file and return a Matrix{Float64}. The expected format is one time column followed by one or more replicate columns:\n\n# t (min)   rep1 (g)   rep2 (g)\n0.0         0.000      0.000\n5.0         0.110      0.094\n10.0        0.257      0.227\n\nLines starting with # are ignored. Keyword arguments are passed to DelimitedFiles.readdlm.\n\nExample\n\ndata = TextTable(\"experiment.txt\")\ncurve = ExtractionCurve(data=data, temperature=313.15, ...)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#SFEModelling.ExcelTable","page":"API Reference","title":"SFEModelling.ExcelTable","text":"ExcelTable(filename; sheet=1, header=true)\n\nRead an Excel .xlsx file and return a Matrix{Float64}. The expected format is one time column followed by one or more replicate columns.\n\nArguments\n\nfilename: path to the .xlsx file.\nsheet: sheet index (default: 1) or name (String).\nheader: whether the first row contains column headers to skip (default: true).\n\nExample\n\ndata = ExcelTable(\"experiment.xlsx\")\ncurve = ExtractionCurve(data=data, temperature=313.15, ...)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#SFEModelling.fit_model","page":"API Reference","title":"SFEModelling.fit_model","text":"fit_model(curve; kwargs...)               → ModelFitResult{Sovova}\nfit_model(curves; kwargs...)              → ModelFitResult{Sovova}\nfit_model(Sovova(), curve; kwargs...)     → ModelFitResult{Sovova}\nfit_model(model, curve; kwargs...)        → ModelFitResult{M}\nfit_model(model, curves; kwargs...)       → ModelFitResult{M}\n\nFit a kinetic SFE model to one or more extraction curves.\n\nWhen called without a model (or with Sovova()), fits the Sovová PDE model and returns a ModelFitResult{Sovova}. Each curve gets its own kya and kxa; the ratio xk/x0 is shared across all curves.\n\nWhen called with any other model type M, fits that empirical model with all parameters shared across curves, and returns a ModelFitResult{M}.\n\nArguments\n\nmodel: kinetic model instance. Defaults to Sovova() when omitted. Empirical options: Esquivel(), Zekovic(), PKM(), SplineModel().\ncurve / curves: a single ExtractionCurve or a Vector of them.\n\nKeyword arguments — Sovová model\n\nkya_bounds::Tuple{Float64,Float64}: bounds for kya (default: (0.0, 0.05))\nkxa_bounds::Tuple{Float64,Float64}: bounds for kxa (default: (0.0, 0.005))\nxk_ratio_bounds::Tuple{Float64,Float64}: bounds for xk/x0 (default: (0.0, 1.0))\nmaxevals::Int: maximum function evaluations (default: 50_000)\ntracemode::Symbol: optimizer verbosity — :silent, :compact, or :verbose (default: :silent)\n\nKeyword arguments — empirical models\n\nparam_bounds::Vector{Tuple{Float64,Float64}}: one bound per parameter; defaults to the values from param_spec\nmaxevals::Int: maximum function evaluations (default: 50_000)\ntracemode::Symbol: optimizer verbosity (default: :silent)\n\nExamples\n\n# Sovová PDE model (default)\nresult = fit_model(curve)\nresult = fit_model(Sovova(), curve)\n\n# Empirical model\nresult = fit_model(PKM(), curve)\nresult = fit_model(PKM(), [curve1, curve2])\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#SFEModelling.param_spec","page":"API Reference","title":"SFEModelling.param_spec","text":"param_spec(model) -> Vector{ParamSpec}\n\nReturn the parameter specification for model: a vector of ParamSpec values, each describing a parameter's name, human-readable label, and default lower/upper bounds.\n\nUsed internally by fit_model to set the search range for the optimizer. Inspect it to see parameter order and default bounds:\n\nparam_spec(PKM())\n# 3-element Vector{ParamSpec}:\n#  \"k1\"  k₁ — easily accessible fraction (—)      [0.0, 1.0]\n#  \"k2\"  k₂ — fluid-phase rate constant (1/s)      [0.0, 0.05]\n#  \"k3\"  k₃ — solid-phase rate constant (1/s)      [0.0, 0.005]\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#SFEModelling.Sovova","page":"API Reference","title":"SFEModelling.Sovova","text":"Sovova()\n\nSovová PDE supercritical extraction model. This is the default model used when calling fit_model without an explicit model argument.\n\nFits per-curve parameters kya (fluid-phase mass transfer coefficient, 1/s) and kxa (solid-phase mass transfer coefficient, 1/s), plus a shared xk/x0 ratio (easily accessible solute fraction).\n\nReturns a ModelFitResult.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"api/#SFEModelling.Esquivel","page":"API Reference","title":"SFEModelling.Esquivel","text":"Esquivel()\n\nSingle-exponential model (Esquível & Bernardo-Gil, 1999):\n\nm_e(t) = m_total(1 - e^-k_1 t)\n\nOne fitted parameter: k1 — rate constant (1/s).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"api/#SFEModelling.Zekovic","page":"API Reference","title":"SFEModelling.Zekovic","text":"Zekovic()\n\nTwo-parameter accessible-fraction model (Žeković et al., 2003):\n\nm_e(t) = m_total k_1(1 - e^-k_2 t)\n\nTwo fitted parameters: k1 — accessible yield fraction (—); k2 — rate constant (1/s).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"api/#SFEModelling.PKM","page":"API Reference","title":"SFEModelling.PKM","text":"PKM()\n\nParallel-kinetics model (Fiori et al., 2012):\n\nm_e(t) = m_totalleftk_1(1 - e^-k_2 t) + (1-k_1)(1 - e^-k_3 t)right\n\nThree fitted parameters: k1 — easily accessible fraction (—); k2 — fluid-phase rate constant (1/s); k3 — solid-phase rate constant (1/s).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"api/#SFEModelling.SplineModel","page":"API Reference","title":"SFEModelling.SplineModel","text":"SplineModel()\n\nPiecewise-linear CER/FER/DC model:\n\nCER phase (0 ≤ t ≤ k₂): m_e = m_totalk_1t\nFER phase (k₂ < t ≤ k₄): m_e = m_CER + m_totalk_3(t - k_2)\nDC phase (t > k₄): m_e = m_FER (constant)\n\nFour fitted parameters: k1 — CER rate (1/s); k2 — CER end time (s); k3 — FER rate (1/s); k4 — FER end time (s).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"api/#SFEModelling.ModelFitResult","page":"API Reference","title":"SFEModelling.ModelFitResult","text":"ModelFitResult{M<:ExtractionModel}\n\nResult of fitting kinetic model M to one or more extraction curves.\n\nAll models return a ModelFitResult{M}. \n\nCommon fields\n\nmodel: the fitted model instance\nycal::Vector{Vector{Float64}}: calculated extraction curves (kg), one per input curve\nobjective::Float64: sum of squared residuals (SSR) at the optimum\n\nSovová-specific properties (accessed via result.field)\n\nkya, kxa, xk_ratio, xk, tcer\n\nEmpirical-model properties (accessed via result.field)\n\nparams, spec\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"api/#SFEModelling.export_results","page":"API Reference","title":"SFEModelling.export_results","text":"export_results(filename, result, curve)\nexport_results(filename, result, curves)\n\nExport fitting results to a file. The format is inferred from the extension:\n\n.xlsx — Excel workbook (one sheet per curve). Parameters occupy columns A–B; the data table (time, experimental replicates, calculated values) starts at column C.\nanything else — space-delimited text. Parameters are written as #-comment lines (readable by TextTable), followed by the data table.\n\nExample\n\nresult = fit_model(curve)\nexport_results(\"results.txt\",  result, curve)\nexport_results(\"results.xlsx\", result, curve)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#SFEModelling.create_shortcut","page":"API Reference","title":"SFEModelling.create_shortcut","text":"create_shortcut(; location=:desktop, port=9876, name=\"SFEModelling\")\n\nCreate a launcher shortcut for the SFEModelling GUI. Supports Windows, macOS, and Linux.\n\nKeyword arguments\n\nlocation: where to install the shortcut:\nWindows: :desktop (default) or :startmenu\nmacOS:   :desktop (default) or :applications (/Applications)\nLinux:   :desktop (default) or :applications (~/.local/share/applications)\nport: port passed to the app (default: 9876).\nname: shortcut name (default: \"SFEModelling\").\n\nExample\n\nusing SFEModelling\ncreate_shortcut()                          # desktop shortcut, default port\ncreate_shortcut(location=:applications)    # app menu entry\ncreate_shortcut(port=8080, name=\"SFE Fit\")\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"usage/#Advanced-usage","page":"Advanced usage","title":"Advanced usage","text":"The advanced usage is based on a programming interface. The package can be run in the Julia REPL, in a Jupyter or Pluto notebook, or in a dedicated programming interface, such as VSCode. Additional tips for a nice programming workflow using Julia can be found at the Modern Julia Workflows.","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Defining-an-extraction-curve","page":"Advanced usage","title":"Defining an extraction curve","text":"Create an ExtractionCurve with your experimental data and operating conditions. All inputs use laboratory units (g, cm, min) — the package converts to SI internally.\n\nThe experimental data is provided as a matrix where column 1 is the extraction time (min) and columns 2, 3, … are cumulative extracted mass (g) for each replicate:\n\nusing SFEModelling\n\n# Single replicate (2 columns: time, m_ext)\ndata = [5.0  0.10;\n        10.0 0.25;\n        15.0 0.42;\n        20.0 0.58;\n        30.0 0.85;\n        45.0 1.10;\n        60.0 1.28;\n        90.0 1.45;\n        120.0 1.52]\n\ncurve = ExtractionCurve(\n    data           = data,\n    porosity       = 0.4,      # dimensionless\n    x0             = 0.05,     # kg/kg (total extractable yield)\n    solid_density  = 1.1,      # g/cm³\n    solvent_density = 0.8,     # g/cm³\n    flow_rate      = 5.0,      # cm³/min\n    bed_height     = 20.0,     # cm\n    bed_diameter   = 2.0,      # cm\n    particle_diameter = 0.05,  # cm\n    solid_mass     = 50.0,     # g\n    solubility     = 0.005,    # kg/kg\n)","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Fitting-a-single-curve","page":"Advanced usage","title":"Fitting a single curve","text":"Call fit_model with an ExtractionCurve. With no model argument it defaults to the Sovová PDE model:\n\nresult = fit_model(curve)\n\nThe returned object is a ModelFitResult.\n\nThe calculated extraction curves (in kg) are available as:\n\nresult.ycal[1]  # calculated values for the first (and only) curve","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Reading-data-from-files","page":"Advanced usage","title":"Reading data from files","text":"Instead of typing the data matrix directly, you can read it from a text or Excel file. Example files are available for download: example_data.txt · example_data.xlsx","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Text-files-with-[TextTable](@ref)","page":"Advanced usage","title":"Text files with TextTable","text":"A whitespace-delimited text file with an optional comment header (lines starting with #):\n\n# t (min)   rep1 (g)   rep2 (g)\n0.0         0.000      0.000\n5.0         0.110      0.094\n10.0        0.257      0.227\n\ndata = TextTable(\"experiment.txt\")\ncurve = ExtractionCurve(data=data, porosity=0.4, ...)","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Excel-files-with-[ExcelTable](@ref)","page":"Advanced usage","title":"Excel files with ExcelTable","text":"An .xlsx file where the first row is a header and the remaining rows contain the data matrix (time column + replicate columns):\n\ndata = ExcelTable(\"experiment.xlsx\")              # reads first sheet, skips header\ndata = ExcelTable(\"experiment.xlsx\"; sheet=2)      # read a specific sheet\ndata = ExcelTable(\"experiment.xlsx\"; header=false)  # no header row to skip\ncurve = ExtractionCurve(data=data, porosity=0.4, ...)","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Discretization","page":"Advanced usage","title":"Discretization","text":"The numerical solution uses finite differences with nh spatial steps and nt temporal steps (defaults: nh=5, nt=2500). Increase nt for better accuracy at the cost of computation time:\n\ncurve = ExtractionCurve(\n    # ... other arguments ...\n    nh = 10,\n    nt = 5000,\n)","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Fitting-multiple-curves-simultaneously","page":"Advanced usage","title":"Fitting multiple curves simultaneously","text":"Pass a vector of ExtractionCurves to fit all curves at once. Each curve gets its own kya and kxa, but the ratio xk/x0 is shared across all curves:\n\ncurve1 = ExtractionCurve(; data=data1, porosity=0.35, ...)\ncurve2 = ExtractionCurve(; data=data2, porosity=0.40, ...)\ncurve3 = ExtractionCurve(; data=data3, porosity=0.45, ...)\n\nresult = fit_model([curve1, curve2, curve3])\n\nAccess per-curve results by index:\n\nresult.kya[2]   # kya for curve 2\nresult.kxa[2]   # kxa for curve 2\nresult.xk[2]    # xk for curve 2\nresult.tcer[2]  # tCER for curve 2\nresult.ycal[2]  # calculated curve 2","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Optimizer-options","page":"Advanced usage","title":"Optimizer options","text":"The fitting uses global optimization from BlackBoxOptim.jl. Control the optimization via keyword arguments:\n\nresult = fit_model(curves;\n    kya_bounds      = (0.0, 0.05),   # bounds for kya (1/s)\n    kxa_bounds      = (0.0, 0.005),  # bounds for kxa (1/s)\n    xk_ratio_bounds = (0.0, 1.0),    # bounds for xk/x0\n    maxevals        = 50_000,        # max function evaluations\n    tracemode       = :silent,       # :silent, :compact, or :verbose\n)\n\nIf the default bounds do not cover your expected parameter range, adjust them accordingly. To see optimizer progress, set tracemode = :compact:\n\nresult = fit_model(curve; tracemode=:compact)","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Complete-example-with-real-data","page":"Advanced usage","title":"Complete example with real data","text":"The following example uses experimental data from a supercritical CO₂ extraction experiment at 333.15 K (data from Mateus et al.), with two replicates:\n\nusing SFEModelling\n\n# Data matrix: column 1 = time (min), columns 2-3 = replicate m_ext (g)\ndata = [\n    0.0   0.0000  0.0000;\n    5.0   0.1097  0.0935;\n   10.0   0.2571  0.2265;\n   15.0   0.3894  0.3507;\n   20.0   0.5228  0.4746;\n   30.0   0.7872  0.7270;\n   45.0   1.1633  1.0636;\n   60.0   1.4848  1.3746;\n   75.0   1.7484  1.6411;\n   90.0   1.9751  1.8913;\n  110.0   2.2485  2.1785;\n  135.0   2.5630  2.5539;\n  155.0   2.7584  2.7690;\n  180.0   3.0323  3.0527;\n  210.0   3.3022  3.3416;\n  240.0   3.5332  3.5906;\n  270.0   3.7349  3.8130;\n  300.0   3.9260  4.0177\n]\n\n# Or read from a file:\n# data = TextTable(\"mateus1.txt\")\n# data = ExcelTable(\"mateus1.xlsx\")\n\ncurve = ExtractionCurve(\n    data              = data,\n    porosity          = 0.7,      # bed porosity (dimensionless)\n    x0                = 0.069,    # total extractable yield (kg/kg)\n    solid_density     = 1.32,     # g/cm³\n    solvent_density   = 0.78023,  # g/cm³\n    flow_rate         = 9.9,      # cm³/min\n    bed_height        = 9.2,      # cm\n    bed_diameter      = 5.42,     # cm\n    particle_diameter = 0.0337,   # cm\n    solid_mass        = 100.01,   # g\n    solubility        = 0.003166, # kg/kg\n)\n\nresult = fit_model(curve)","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Fitting-alternative-kinetic-models","page":"Advanced usage","title":"Fitting alternative kinetic models","text":"In addition to the Sovová PDE model, SFEModelling provides several empirical kinetic models that can be fitted with fit_model:\n\nModel type Reference Parameters\nEsquivel() Esquivel (1999) k₁ — rate constant (1/s)\nZekovic() Žeković (2003) k₁ — accessible yield fraction (—); k₂ — rate constant (1/s)\nPKM() Fiori et al. (2012) k₁ — easily accessible fraction (—); k₂ — fluid-phase rate (1/s); k₃ — solid-phase rate (1/s)\nSplineModel() — k₁ — CER rate (1/s); k₂ — CER end time (s); k₃ — FER rate (1/s); k₄ — FER end time (s)","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Single-curve-fit","page":"Advanced usage","title":"Single-curve fit","text":"result = fit_model(Esquivel(), curve)","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Multi-curve-fit","page":"Advanced usage","title":"Multi-curve fit","text":"When a vector of curves is passed, all model parameters are shared across curves:\n\nresult = fit_model(PKM(), [curve, curve, curve])\n\nprintln(result.ycal[2])   # calculated curve 2 (kg)","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Custom-parameter-bounds","page":"Advanced usage","title":"Custom parameter bounds","text":"Each model has default parameter bounds (see param_spec). Override them with the param_bounds keyword — a vector of (lower, upper) tuples, one per parameter:\n\nresult = fit_model(PKM(), curve;\n    param_bounds = [(0.0, 1.0), (0.0, 0.01), (0.0, 0.001)],\n    maxevals     = 100_000,\n    tracemode    = :compact,\n)","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Accessing-results","page":"Advanced usage","title":"Accessing results","text":"The returned ModelFitResult stores fitted parameters in result.params in the same order as the model's parameter list:\n\nresult = fit_model(Zekovic(), curve)\nprintln(result.params[1])  # k1 — accessible yield fraction\nprintln(result.params[2])  # k2 — rate constant (1/s)\nprintln(result.ycal[1])    # calculated curve (kg)\nprintln(result.objective)  # SSR","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Exporting-results","page":"Advanced usage","title":"Exporting results","text":"Use export_results to write fitting results to a file. The format is determined by the file extension — .xlsx produces an Excel workbook; any other extension produces a space-delimited text file with parameters as #-comment lines (re-readable by TextTable):\n\nexport_results(\"results.txt\",  result, curve)   # text file\nexport_results(\"results.xlsx\", result, curve)   # Excel workbook\nexport_results(\"results.txt\",  result, [curve1, curve2])  # multiple curves\n\nAll results share the same show format:\n\njulia> result                       # Zekovic example\nModelFitResult{Zekovic} — 1 curve fitted\n  SSR = 4.2000e-06\n\n  Parameter │         Value │ Description\n  ──────────┼───────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────\n  k1        │ +8.200000e-01 │ k₁ — accessible yield fraction (—)\n  k2        │ +3.100000e-04 │ k₂ — rate constant (1/s)\n\njulia> result                       # Sovová default, 2 curves\nModelFitResult{Sovova} — 2 curves fitted\n  SSR = 3.8021e-07\n\n  Parameter │         Value │ Description\n  ──────────┼───────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n  xk/x0     │ +6.521700e-01 │ xk/x₀ — accessible solute ratio (—)\n  kya[1]    │ +2.000000e-02 │ kya — fluid-phase mass transfer coeff. (1/s)\n  kxa[1]    │ +2.000000e-03 │ kxa — solid-phase mass transfer coeff. (1/s)\n  tCER[1]   │ +1.234500e+03 │ tCER — CER period duration (s)\n  kya[2]    │ +1.500000e-02 │ kya — fluid-phase mass transfer coeff. (1/s)\n  kxa[2]    │ +1.800000e-03 │ kxa — solid-phase mass transfer coeff. (1/s)\n  tCER[2]   │ +1.543200e+03 │ tCER — CER period duration (s)","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Graphical-User-Interface","page":"Advanced usage","title":"Graphical User Interface","text":"See the GUI page for the built-in web interface.","category":"section"},{"location":"gui/#Graphical-User-Interface","page":"GUI","title":"Graphical User Interface","text":"SFEModelling includes a built-in web GUI — no extra packages or configuration required. By following the Installation instructions you should be able the launch the GUI by clicking on the desktop icon that is generated.","category":"section"},{"location":"gui/#Launch-it-directly-from-the-Julia-REPL:","page":"GUI","title":"Launch it directly from the Julia REPL:","text":"If the desktop icon is not available, or if you experience issues with the icon launcher,  you can, after installing the Julia package, run it from the REPL, with:\n\nusing SFEModelling\nsfegui()\n\nThis starts a local HTTP server and opens your default browser at http://127.0.0.1:9876.","category":"section"},{"location":"gui/#Features","page":"GUI","title":"Features","text":"In the browser interface you can:\n\nUpload a data file (.txt, .csv, .dat, or .xlsx) with time and replicate columns — example_data.txt · example_data.xlsx\nSelect a kinetic model from a dropdown (Sovová, Esquível, Žeković, PKM, or Spline)\nFill in all operating conditions through form fields (porosity, densities, flow rate, etc.)\nConfigure optimizer bounds for each model's parameters (bounds update automatically when the model is changed) and set the maximum number of evaluations\nRun the fitting and see results directly in the browser\nDownload the results as a .txt or .xlsx file\n\nNo Julia code required — everything is done through the graphical form.","category":"section"},{"location":"gui/#Options","page":"GUI","title":"Options","text":"sfegui(port=8080, launch=false)\n\nKeyword Default Description\nport 9876 Local port for the HTTP server\nlaunch true Automatically open the browser","category":"section"},{"location":"gui/#Stopping-the-server","page":"GUI","title":"Stopping the server","text":"Press Ctrl-C in the REPL, or call close(server) on the returned server object:\n\nserver = sfegui()\n# ... use the GUI ...\nclose(server)","category":"section"},{"location":"gui/#API","page":"GUI","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"gui/#SFEModelling.sfegui","page":"GUI","title":"SFEModelling.sfegui","text":"sfegui(; port=9876, launch=true)\n\nLaunch a local web-based GUI for SFEModelling.\n\nOpens a browser window at http://localhost:$port where you can:\n\nUpload a data file (text or Excel) with time and replicate columns\nFill in all operating conditions\nConfigure optimizer bounds and maximum evaluations\nRun the fitting and see results directly in the browser\n\nPress Ctrl-C in the REPL to stop the server, or call close(server) on the returned HTTP.Server object.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"model/#Model-Description","page":"Model","title":"Model Description","text":"SFEModelling implements eight kinetic models for supercritical fluid extraction (SFE). All models relate cumulative extracted mass m_e(t) to time t. The total extractable mass is m_T = x_0 cdot m_s, where x_0 is the initial solute loading (kg/kg) and m_s is the solid mass (kg).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"model/#Sovová-(1994)-—-Broken-and-Intact-Cells","page":"Model","title":"Sovová (1994) — Broken and Intact Cells","text":"The only mechanistic model in the set. It distinguishes two fractions of the solid: easily accessible solute (outside broken cells) and solute trapped inside intact cells. Extraction proceeds through three consecutive phases: constant extraction rate (CER), falling extraction rate (FER), and diffusion-controlled (DC).","category":"section"},{"location":"model/#Mass-balance-equations","page":"Model","title":"Mass balance equations","text":"Coupled PDEs along the bed height h:\n\nFluid phase:\n\nvarepsilon  v  fracpartial Ypartial h = J(X Y)\n\nSolid phase:\n\n(1 - varepsilon)rho_sfracpartial Xpartial t = -rho_fJ(X Y)","category":"section"},{"location":"model/#Mass-transfer-rate","page":"Model","title":"Mass transfer rate","text":"J = begincases\n  k_Y a (Y^* - Y)  X  x_k quad text(CER) 4pt\n  k_X a  X left(1 - dfracYY^*right)  X le x_k quad text(FER)\nendcases\n\nFitted parameters (per curve, except xk/x0 which is shared across curves):\n\nSymbol Description\nkya (k_Y a) Fluid-phase volumetric mass-transfer coefficient (1/s)\nkxa (k_X a) Solid-phase volumetric mass-transfer coefficient (1/s)\nxk/x0 (x_kx_0) Fraction of easily accessible solute\n\nThe PDE is solved numerically by the method of lines (upwind finite differences + explicit Euler).\n\nReference: Sovová, H. (1994). Chem. Eng. Sci., 49(3), 409–414. doi:10.1016/0009-2509(94)87012-8\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"model/#Esquível-(1999)","page":"Model","title":"Esquível (1999)","text":"Single-exponential empirical model derived from a simplified mass balance:\n\nm_e(t) = m_T left(1 - e^-k_1 tright)\n\nSymbol Description\nk_1 Rate constant (1/s); physically related to solubility and flow conditions\n\nReference: Esquível, M.M.; Bernardo-Gil, M.G.; King, M.B. (1999). J. Supercrit. Fluids, 16(1), 43–58. doi:10.1016/S0896-8446(99)00014-5\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"model/#Zekovic-(2003)","page":"Model","title":"Zekovic (2003)","text":"Two-parameter model separating the accessible yield fraction from the extraction rate:\n\nm_e(t) = m_T  k_1 left(1 - e^-k_2 tright)\n\nSymbol Description\nk_1 Accessible yield fraction (dimensionless, 0–1)\nk_2 Rate constant (1/s)\n\nReference: Zeković, Z.P. et al. (2003). Acta Period. Technol., 34, 125–133. doi\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"model/#PKM-—-Parallel-Reaction-Kinetics-(Maksimovic,-2012)","page":"Model","title":"PKM — Parallel Reaction Kinetics (Maksimovic, 2012)","text":"Interprets extraction as parallel first-order \"reactions\" from two solid fractions:\n\nm_e(t) = m_T left k_1 left(1 - e^-k_2 tright) + (1 - k_1)left(1 - e^-k_3 tright) right\n\nSymbol Description\nk_1 Easily accessible solute fraction (dimensionless, 0–1)\nk_2 Fluid-phase rate constant (1/s)\nk_3 Solid-phase rate constant (1/s), k_3  k_2\n\nReference: Maksimović, S.; Ivanović, J.; Skala, D. (2012). Procedia Eng., 42, 1767–1777. doi:10.1016/j.proeng.2012.07.571\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"model/#Spline-—-Piecewise-linear-CER/FER/DC-(Rodrigues,-2003)","page":"Model","title":"Spline — Piecewise-linear CER/FER/DC (Rodrigues, 2003)","text":"Fits the extraction curve with three straight-line segments, one per extraction phase:\n\nm_e(t) = begincases\n  m_Tk_1t  t le k_2 quad text(CER) 4pt\n  m_Tk_1k_2 + m_Tk_3(t - k_2)  k_2  t le k_4 quad text(FER) 4pt\n  m_Tk_1k_2 + m_Tk_3(k_4 - k_2)  t  k_4 quad text(DC flat)\nendcases\n\nSymbol Description\nk_1 CER extraction rate (1/s)\nk_2 End time of CER phase (s)\nk_3 FER extraction rate (1/s), k_3  k_1\nk_4 End time of FER phase (s), k_4  k_2\n\nReference: Rodrigues, V.M. et al. (2003). J. Agric. Food Chem., 51(6), 1518–1523. doi:10.1021/jf0257493\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"model/#Parameter-estimation","page":"Model","title":"Parameter estimation","text":"All models minimize the sum of squared residuals (SSR):\n\ntextSSR = sum_i=1^N_textcurves sum_j=1^m_i\nleft( m_etextcalj^(i) - m_etextexpj^(i) right)^2\n\nFor empirical models, all parameters are shared across curves. For the Sovová model, kya and kxa are per-curve while xk/x0 is shared.\n\nOptimization uses BlackBoxOptim.jl, a derivative-free global optimizer that handles non-convex, bound-constrained problems without manual multi-start.","category":"section"},{"location":"installation/#Installation","page":"Installation","title":"Installation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"installation/#Windows","page":"Installation","title":"Windows","text":"For Windows we provide an installer which should take care of all the steps: \n\nDownload Windows Installer\n\nThe installer will: \n\nInstall the Julia language if not yet available. \nInstall the SFEModelling application.\nAdd an icon to your desktop.","category":"section"},{"location":"installation/#Manual-step-by-step-installation","page":"Installation","title":"Manual step-by-step installation","text":"The manual installation can be performed on all platforms (Linux/MacOS/Windows), and is necessary for the advanced (command-line) use of the package.  \n\nThere are to installation modes: the SFEModelling Application and the SFEModelling Package. \n\nThe Application is a standalone executable, linked to the desktop icon, and that allows the execution of the package using the graphical user interface. \nThe Package has the same functionalities, but is accessible through the Julia REPL (the terminal) and can be used for advanced scripting, large-scale multiple fits, etc. Installation of the package also gives access to the graphical user interface.","category":"section"},{"location":"installation/#1.-Installing-Julia","page":"Installation","title":"1. Installing Julia","text":"Install Julia following the instructions of the official Julia distribution page: https://julialang.org/downloads/.","category":"section"},{"location":"installation/#2.-Installing-the-SFEModelling-Application","page":"Installation","title":"2. Installing the SFEModelling Application","text":"Start the Julia REPL (which will open the julia> terminal), use these commands:\n\njulia> import Pkg; Pkg.Apps.add(\"SFEModelling\")\n\nThis will add an icon to your desktop, with which you can start the graphical user interface.","category":"section"},{"location":"installation/#3.-Installing-the-SFEModelling-Package","page":"Installation","title":"3. Installing the SFEModelling Package","text":"The SFEModelling package is installed similarly, but provides the advanced (command-line) interface that allows programming tasks. Installation is performed with the following command:\n\njulia> import Pkg; Pkg.add(\"SFEModelling\")\n\nThe package is then used with:\n\njulia> using SFEModelling\n\nThe graphical user interface can also be launched, by executing the sfegui() command.\n\ntip: Advanced usage tips\nIf you use VS Code for programming and scripting, install the Julia extension for syntax highlighting, inline evaluation, and an integrated REPL.","category":"section"},{"location":"installation/#Updating","page":"Installation","title":"Updating","text":"To update the Application, start the Jula REPL and use:\n\njulia> import Pkg; Pkg.Apps.update(\"SFEModelling\")\n\nTo update the Package, use:\n\njulia> import Pkg; Pkg.update(\"SFEModelling\")","category":"section"},{"location":"#SFEModelling.jl","page":"Home","title":"SFEModelling.jl","text":"Kinetic model fitting for supercritical fluid extraction.\n\n(Image: Build Status) (Image: Documentation) (Image: Documentation)","category":"section"},{"location":"#Overview","page":"Home","title":"Overview","text":"SFEModelling.jl fits kinetic models for supercritical fluid extraction (SFE) to one or more experimental extraction curves. The package:\n\nAccepts experimental data and operating conditions in laboratory units (g, cm, min).\nSupports 8 kinetic models, from a rigorous PDE model to simple empirical correlations.\nFits model parameters using global optimization from BlackBoxOptim.jl — no manual multi-start needed.\nProvides a graphical interface accessible via desktop shortcut or sfegui().","category":"section"},{"location":"#Supported-models","page":"Home","title":"Supported models","text":"Model Parameters Description\nSovová (1994) kya, kxa, xk/x0 PDE — broken & intact cells; multi-curve with shared xk/x0\nEsquível (1999) k1 Empirical — single exponential\nZekovic (2003) k1, k2 Empirical — accessible fraction × exponential\nPKM — Maksimovic (2012) k1, k2, k3 Parallel-reaction kinetics\nSpline — Rodrigues (2003) k1–k4 Piecewise-linear CER/FER/DC\n\nSee the Models page for the equations.","category":"section"},{"location":"#References","page":"Home","title":"References","text":"Sovová, H. Rate of the vegetable oil extraction with supercritical CO₂ — I. Modelling of extraction curves. Chemical Engineering Science, v. 49, n. 3, p. 409–414, 1994. doi:10.1016/0009-2509(94)87012-8\nMartínez, J.; Martínez, J.M. Fitting the Sovová's supercritical fluid extraction model by means of a global optimization tool. Computers & Chemical Engineering, v. 32, n. 8, p. 1735–1745, 2008. doi:10.1016/j.compchemeng.2007.08.016\nMartínez, J.; Monteiro, A.R.; Rosa, P.T.V.; Marques, M.O.M.; Meireles, M.A.A. Multicomponent model to describe extraction of ginger oleoresin with supercritical carbon dioxide. Industrial & Engineering Chemistry Research, v. 42, n. 5, p. 1057–1063, 2003. doi:10.1021/ie020694f","category":"section"}]
}
